arch:property.oc:show_val: This locus is the cobble collapse area along the north baulk. It consists of many flat lying cobbles and flagstones. The width of the structure varies. We have a window into a second layer of stones at the north baulk via a feature that I thought was a pit but is a hard packed layer of clay and silt loam on top of a second course of stones, two of which are flagstones larger than any of the other stones. The area at the north baulk looks more like a wall than the rest of the rocks. There are a lot of basalt grindstones visible.
tightly spaced cobbles with slightly packed silt between, one area of very hard packed silt over second course stones
large and small cobbles, some pot sherds, basalt grindstones, flagstones

arch:note.arch:string: Contexts excavated in trenches were recorded using the "locus system." A locus is any discrete three-dimensional entity excavated in a trench. The key to the locus system is the recognition that a locus is any one thing. Differences in soil composition or texture are therefore as important as, for example, the difference between a pit and a wall. If two entities were distinct, they were considered separate loci and were therefore assigned separate locus numbers. It should also be noted that every context excavated in a trench was given a locus number and thus the trench itself is made up completely of excavated loci.
